Commentary.Commentary: We are back! The Pakistani players have made their way out into the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and Kieran Powell are the openers for West Indies. Mohammad Abbas to begin with the ball. Here we go...

Right then. This will be a nervy phase for the Windies openers, as there is not much time left, nor are there many overs. They will want to stay out there without losing a single wicket. Will they be able to do so? Stay tuned to find out...

Just what West Indies needed with the ball. They have bowled with intent, purpose, and zest to bowl Pakistan out for a decent score. Jason Holder was definitely the pick of the lot, as he finished with 3 to his name, while also being economical. Jayden Seales was slightly expensive but still got three wickets. Kemar Roach again showed his skill, ending with a wicket to his name. Overall, though, this was a combined bowling effort from the hosts.

Pakistan did not really have the best outing with the blade in this innings, but a couple of batting displays helped them post a decent total. They lost their openers early and just when it seemed like Azhar Ali and Babar Azam were going along nicely, this stand was broken too. Azam and Rizwan did not hang around for long too. Fawad Alam and Faheem Ashraf stitched an 85-run, which was looking solid, but once this was broken, Pakistan just kept losing wickets and folded for 217.

A really good bowling display by the hosts has seen them bundle out Pakistan for 217. The visitors will not be too unhappy about how things have panned out, as they got a couple of runs towards the end of the innings, but they would have wanted to cross the 250-run mark.

For Pakistan, the runs are not flowing and on the other hand, the wickets were tumbling down. Azhar Ali and Azam were looking good in the middle but the former departed for 17, and Azam followed him as he gave away his wicket in the very next over. He departed on 30. Rizwan and Alam stayed in the middle together but Rizwan went back for quick 23. Alam and Ashraf are battling hard in the middle and would look to up the run rate in the next session. Will they be able to do so? Join us for the third session at 3.50 pm local (8.50 pm GMT).

This session was all about the hosts. Three wickets for them after the Lunch session and with half of the Pakistani team back, they have the upper hand right now over Pakistan. Azhar Ali was the first big wicket after the Lunch session, courtesy of Jayden Seals. Babar Azam followed him as Kemar Roach got the prized wicket of him. Holder got rid of Rizwan. West Indies will look to take quick wickets in the next session and bundle the hosts out for a tame score.

He could have really taken the game away from them, but he does not have the desired impact in this innings. On a length, around off, nipping in, Azam looks to defend this one out, but the ball seams in and beats his inside edge, to the keeper, who takes it and appeals. Update 12.45 pm local (5.45 pm GMT) - Some more good news now. The rain has flown by and the covers have been completely removed as well. The groundsmen are still trying to mop up the region near the bowler's landing and near the outfield as well. We are being told that play will resume at 1 pm local (6 pm GMT), but we are still awaiting the official word, which should be out soon enough. The timing has been confirmed. Let's hope we do not have any more delays now.

Update 12.25 pm local (5.25 pm GMT) - Good news! The rain has stopped and the atmosphere has become slightly brighter as well. The groundsmen are ensuring that the covers come off cleanly. The two umpires are having a stroll and we should have some more information soon enough. Stay tuned for further updates.

Update 12.10 pm local (5.10 pm GMT) - Unfortunately, we do not have good news to greet you with, as it is still raining at the moment. The covers are firmly in place and the two umpires are out in the middle too, with umbrellas over them. The start of the second session will be delayed. Let's hope the conditions improve soon. Stay tuned.
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

We could have just 17 overs but they were very well bowled by West Indies. They keep on showing their potential in the longest format of the game but somehow are not able to keep that going consistently. Kemar Roach bowled with fire while Jayden Seales continues to show what a great bowler he could be for the future. Looking at the conditions, one does feel that West Indies are one fast bowler light, as the likes of Alzarri Joseph could have made merry in these conditions. But this is just the opening session of a 5-day Test. Join us back at 12.10 pm local (1710 GMT) for the second session, anticipating of course, that the rain would have gone away by then.

It has been an excellent morning for the home side. They were on the mark from the word go, extracting all the juice available from the pitch and then, making use of Pakistan's inexperienced opening pair. There is nothing much to talk about in Imran Butt and Abid Ali and Pakistan were two down by the 8th over. Since then, the experience of Azhar Ali and Babar Azam has kept the hosts at bay.

11.30 am local (1630 GMT) - It is official. EARLY LUNCH HAS BEEN TAKEN. Sensible decision from the umpires, rather than waiting for the scheduled time to take the break. The forecast looks iffy throughout the Test but we can at least hope for positive news.

Cricket updates - Meanwhile, in London, India are lording the game at the moment over England. They are comfortably placed at 203/2 in 65 overs, with KL Rahul once again amongst the runs, batting on 17 short of a ton. Skipper Virat Kohli is slowly but steadily helping himself to some form. One has to say, the English bowling attack has looked toothless in the absence of Stuart Broad.

And as if to suggest their presence, the clouds have burst open and it is raining heavily. Off go the players. The ground staff has come in full force to cover the pitch. We are no weather experts but just get the feeling that this could be a big delay. And as we debate about our expertise, on come more covers. Might as well take an early Lunch.

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), Kieran Powell, Nkrumah Bonner, Kyle Mayers, Roston Chase, Jermaine Blackwood, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Jason Holder, Kemar Roach, Jayden Seales, Jomel Warrican.
TOSS - We are all in readiness for the flip of the coin. WEST INDIES have won the toss and have elected to FIELD first.

WEATHER - Some good news to start this Test. The weather right now is nice and sunny. Although, there is rain expected to pay a visit later on in the day and it is also forecasted throughout the five days. Right now though, it is looking very good.

West Indies can be termed as the underdogs against this Pakistani side. They have not been at their best in this format, as even in their last assignment against South Africa, they folded easily and lost the series 2-0. Their batting has not risen on occasions when the hosts have needed them to and there will be more focus on them in this game. Their bowling has been fairly decent, but they need to start delivering as a team, if they are to cause an upset here. Both the teams will be looking to start with a win, as this series also marks the commencement of their second cycle of the World Test Championship and a win will give them valuable points. It should be an interesting clash. Toss and team news in a bit.

Pakistan will definitely be heading into this series with more confidence as they have been really consistent in this format, in their last couple of assignments. They defeated South Africa and Zimbabwe 2-0 respectively and showed that they had a strong unit. But, playing in the Caribbean is not going to be easy. Even though West Indies have not been at their best at home for a while, it will still be a hard task to trump them. The Asians have the ammunition in the ranks, but, will they come good here? We shall find out.

Hello, folks! After a very damp start to this tour, as out of the 4 T20I games that were scheduled between West Indies and Pakistan, 3 out of them were washed out and we were only treated to one game. Now, from a white-ball, we shift to white jerseys. The 2-game Test series between these two is upon us and hopefully, the rain does not make an appearance and lets us enjoy some uninterrupted cricket, but alas, the forecast is not too great for the first Test. Regardless, let's hope that we get some quality cricket throughout the course of the next 5 days.

We are back! The West Indian players make their way out here. Abid Ali and Imran Butt are the openers for Pakistan. Kemar Roach will begin with the ball. Here he comes...

Right then. The lead of 36 is not a big one for the visitors and they will look to cut that deficit down to a lead, without losing any wickets firstly. Will they do it? Join us for Pakistan's second innings shortly...

This has been a very good bowling display by the Pakistanis. They did take their time and seemed to be on the back foot when Brathwaite was going along, but apart from that, they kept things tight and never let the hosts run away with the game. Apart from Yasir Shah, all of their bowlers got at least a wicket to their name, with the likes of Shaheen Afridi and Mohammad Abbas ending with 4 and 3 respectively. Hasan Ali and Faheem Ashraf were good too, ending with a wicket each.

Kraigg Brathwaite. This is what the Windies batting was about. Sure, there were others who played their role, but it was the captain, who was leading from the front. He got a brilliant 97 but will be sad to have missed out, as he got run out. Jason Holder was brilliant as well, getting a well-deserved 58, but he could not continue. Blackwood, Chase, and Da Silva played small hands, but nothing too big to out shadow their skipper's knock. The other batters disappointed and did not leave their mark. Had they contributed, their lead could have been something bigger.

There it is! It has just taken Pakistan 16 balls on Day 3 to bundle the hosts out and remove the last 2 wickets, that were needed. West Indies end their first innings on 253 and they are leading by 36 runs. Pakistan will be mighty pleased with their work so far.

Just some information if you were not aware of the same. There was a 7.2 magnitude earthquake in Jamaica but everyone related to this Test match are safe and sound and hence, the action will begin at the scheduled time, which is 10 am local (3 pm GMT).

At this point in the game, both teams will have their work cut out for them. West Indies are 8 down and are ahead by 34 runs, and their hopes to get a heftier lead lies on Joshua Da Silva, as he is the only recognized batter out there. Pakistan, on the flip side, knows that they have an opportunity on their hands as they will look to take the remaining 2 wickets quickly and cut down that deficit. Which team will be able to chalk out their plans well? We'll find out as we move along...

Hello and a warm welcome to the moving day of the first Test between West Indies and Pakistan. On Day 2, it was mostly the day of the hosts, as they batted throughout the day, and it was only due to the knocks by Kraigg Brathwaite and also a valuable contribution from Jason Holder. Usually, the moving day lets us know about where the Test match is going and today will be no different. Both the teams will fight tooth and nail and will look to get closer to their desired result. Let's hope for a cracking day of cricket.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Right then! That's all from this day! West Indies are right on top at the moment but they would look to get a lead of as much as possible on Day 3. Pakistan would look to wrap up this innings quickly. Day 3 will begin on 14th August 2021 at 10.00 am Local (3.00 pm GMT) Till then, Goodbye and Take Care!

Pakistan's bowling was not too bad. They started decently and kept it very tight at the start. But the wickets were hard to come by and they needed to fight hard for it. Hasan Ali started it all by picking up the wicket of Roston Chase. Shaheen Afridi was the star in the second session though as he was simply unplayable in that spell. The third session did not go their way as Jason Holder and Kraigg Brathwaite kept them at bay. Mohammad Abbas was decent while Faheem Ashraf bowled really well and was rewarded with a wicket. They would be a little disappointed though that they gave some runs towards the end of the day.

West Indies started the day on 2 for 2 with Roston Chase and Kraigg Brathwaite at the crease. They both started slowly and both were looking good before Chase threw it away. Blackwood looked good before he too played a poor shot and Mayers followed him soon after. Then came the partnership which put West Indies back on track. Jason Holder and Kraigg Brathwaite played superbly helped West Indies get closer to the lead. Brathwaite missed out on a well-deserved century and they were on the verge of getting bowled out but Joshua Da Silva and Kemar Roach helped them end the day on a high, despite Roach losing his wicket towards the fag end of the day.

A good session for West Indies and a good day overall for them! Pakistan will not be too displeased with their effort. They gave it their all and bowled well. They beat the outside edge many times but were unlucky towards the end of the second session. The visitors will be happy to see the form of Shaheen Afridi who was lethal in his spell after Lunch. He picked up the two wickets to fall and was looking unplayable at that moment. Mohammad Abbas was decent as well while Yasir Shah bowled a few overs without much of an impact. A big third session coming up which will begin at 1500 local (2000 GMT). Do join us then.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the first Test match between West Indies and Pakistan. It was an engrossing first Day and the match is nicely poised at the moment. West Indies bowled well to bowl out Pakistan for 217 but the visitors ended the day well, picking up two wickets in 4 overs. Day 2 promises more exciting action, if weather permits. What will happen?
... Day 2, Session 1 ...
Right then. It has been a great day of cricket for both teams and they will look to build on the same. The action on Day 2 will begin at 10 am local (3 pm GMT). Do join us then. Cheers!

Jason Holder is in for a quick chat! He says that they had few days to prepare for the Test. Says that the pitch was quite slow then he expected. Adds that the bowlers were disciplined today and he is very happy. Says that their batters played really well and on Day 2, they have to stitch partnerships in the middle.

West Indies bowled superbly. Not just one or two of their bowlers, but all of them. Sure, their two spinners did not have any wickets to their name, but they applied the pressure whenever needed. Jason Holder and Jayden Seales ended with 3 wickets each, Kemar Roach got two, whereas Kyle Mayers ended with one. Their fielding was also very solid and they did not let a lot of chances go by. With the bat though, they really could not do what they came out to do, as they lost consecutive wickets and finished Day 1 on a poor note.

Not a day that Pakistan would really be happy about. It is not that they played really bad, but they will know that they could have done better. Most of their batters did not really step up and take responsibility. They have relied on Azam and Rizwan for too long and they did not deliver today. Fawad Alam and Faheem Ashraf had a handy stand, which helped Pakistan cross the 200-run mark, but once it was broken, they just fell apart. In fact, they lost their last 5 wickets, scoring just 31 runs, which is a poor number, based on their standards. Mohammad Abbas was on fire, as he took back-to-back wickets and ended the day on a high for the visitors.

This has been a great day of cricket for the hosts, but they will be disheartened that they lost two wickets before stumps on Day 1! They bowled with heart and ensured that Pakistan does not run away with the game, but a double-strike by Abbas, late on Day 1 means that the spoils are shared between these two.

Hello and a warm welcome to the 4th day's play between West Indies and Pakistan. Pakistan have done well to bring themselves back in the game as they lead by 124 and still have 5 wickets in hand. Babar Azam is still out there in the middle and is looking in good touch while Faheem Ashraf has supported him well. West Indies would look to wrap up the innings as quickly as possible before the lead goes out of hand. An exciting contest awaits us on Day 4.

Right then. Pakistan will be looking to swell their lead up to something huge, whereas, West Indies will be hoping to restrict them from doing the same. The action on Day 4 will begin 30 minutes earlier, due to the time lost due to rain and the first ball will be bowled at 9.30 am local (2.30 pm GMT). Do join us then. Cheers and take care!

Jayden Seales is down for a chat. He says that he is enjoying bowling on the surface so far. Adds that something around 200 would be a good target on this wicket. Signs off by saying that they will look to pick up early wickets on Day 4.

West Indies will not be too displeased with how this day has panned out, but after taking 5 wickets, they would have wanted to take one or two more, probably the wicket of Babar Azam, which would have put them in the driving seat. Kemar Roach was on fire, as he kept things tight and also took 2 wickets. Seales, unlike Roach, went for some runs, but his over, in which he took 2 wickets, turned the tide for the hosts. Holder got the big wicket of Rizwan too, which was an important one.
Tossed up, down leg. Babar Azam pads it away and the ball deflects off his pads and races away to the boundary. The Umpire signals it as a dead ball. THAT IS STUMPS ON DAY 3!

Pakistan started off the day very nicely, as, in just 16 balls, they dismissed the hosts out, and ended the first innings of West Indies, behind by 36 runs. Their openers did not show any resistance as Imran Butt was sent packing early. Azhar Ali and Abid Ali showed some fight, but in no time, these two, along with Fawad Alam were back in the hut. It was then, that Babar Azam and Mohammad Rizwan came together and decided to take matters into their own hands. They raised a 56-run stand, but Holder got the better of Rizwan too, after the rain break. Azam got to his fifty and in the able company of Ashraf, they both got through Stumps on Day 3, without any more casualties.

Another great day of Test cricket is what these two sides have served us. Yes, there was a delay due to the rain, but apart from that, it has been a smooth ride on the moving day. At the end of Day 3, Pakistan will have a wider smile, as even though they lost 5 wickets, they still have Babar Azam out in the middle, and also have a lead of 124 to their name.

A session, which you would say was shared between both sides. Pakistan would be the slightly happier side, as after being in a spot of bother, they have done well, courtesy Babar Azam and Mohammad Rizwan. It was an over by Jayden Seales, which opened the floodgates as he removed Abid Ali and Fawad Alam in that one over, which pushed the Asians on the back foot. Then, the duo of Azam and Rizwan came together and did extremely well to steady the ship and take them to safer shores. They played sensibly early on, but when they settled in, they started playing their strokes. Pakistan are ahead by 81 runs and will look to come out and build on the same. The Men in Maroon know that they need to break this stand and will look to do that, and then, pick some more wickets quickly. Join us for the third session at around 2.40 pm local (7.40 pm GMT), if the rain has eased down, by then.

For the hosts, things have not been as planned in the first session on Day 3. First, they would have wanted to swell that lead to somewhere around the 70 or 80-run mark, but they only managed to get a 36 run lead. With the ball too, they would have been mighty pleased if they could have taken one more wicket but will be happy that two Pakistani batters were sent packing. Kemar Roach has bowled well, as he took two wickets. Holder, too, has been pretty effective with the ball in hand, but he missed a catch in the slips, which by his standards, should have been snaffled. The hosts will be looking to take wickets continuously, while Pakistan will want to build on their lead. The second session will be an interesting one. It will begin at 12.40 pm local (5.40 pm GMT). Join us shortly!

A really good session of play for Pakistan. They needed to remove the 2 wickets quickly and they did that in just 16 balls in this morning session. Shaheen struck early and also twice to bundle the Windies out, with a lead of 36. The Pakistani openers again did not show any resistance as Imran Butt was sent packing very early. After that, both the Ali's - Azhar and Abid have done well to stay out there and have also raised a 50-plus run stand, to ensure that they get a lead to their name, but right at the end of the first session, Azhar Ali was sent packing. Kraigg Brathwaite says this match was remarkable and to come out victorious is really amazing. Goes onto say he thinks that Pakistan bowled really well but the patience, in the end, paid off. Mentions they have been working hard as a batting group and knew Pakistan will come hard at them, but his team managed to get over the line with all the hard work and patience.

Jayden Seales, Man of the Match. Says he is happy to get 5 wickets and to perform to the best of his abilities. Mentions that he stayed positive throughout and in the end that paid off. He praises his bowling coach to be patient with him and help him grow as a better cricketer. All the bowlers in the team supported him throughout. Mentions he only aimed to stick in the middle with Roach and it helped.

Babar Azam is up for a chat, he says, they had a good effort with the bat and when they got the momentum they lost quick wickets. In the second innings, they tried to put up runs but West Indies came out on top with their amazing performance. Mentions West Indies bowled really well and they tried to build partnerships but still fell a bit short. Adds that his bowlers bowled really well, especially Shaheen Afridi. Also says a few drop catches in the field cost them the game.

Kemar Roach, is up for a chat. He says he just backed himself and took on every ball as it came and they ended up winning the Test game. Goes onto say, he has been always a part of the tail, and to get the winning runs feels amazing. Mentions he expected the ball to come there and he was ready to hit the winning runs. Goes onto say Seales helped a lot in the middle and credits him to stick till the end.

West Indies had a decent lead but Pakistan came back well with the bat. It was their skipper who played a good knock and he was well supported by Mohammad Rizwan and Faheem Ashraf. They collapsed at the start of Day 4 and they eventually gave a target of 168. Jayden Seales was brilliant with the ball for the hosts. He became the youngest bowler to pick up a 5-fer for West Indies and he was helped by Kemar Roach. In the end, it was a very good performance.

When West Indies came out to bat, it was Kraigg Brathwaite who led the team with the bat as he scored 97 and was the reason that they managed a lead. Jason Holder was the other batter who played a fine knock. Pakistan's bowling was good with Shaheen Afridi and Mohammad Abbas being the pick of the bowlers. Faheem Ashraf too was decent.

Story of the match, After opting to bowl first, West Indies bowled superbly to bowl out Pakistan for just 217. Jayden  Seales and Kemar Roach were stars with the ball as they had 5 wickets among them. For Pakistan, Fawad Alam and Faheem Ashraf were the only ones who got going and if not for them, they would have finished with a very low score.

We have just witnessed a thriller and who told Test matches are boring? The Men in Maroon have gone 1-0 in the 2-game Test series. A hard-fought win for West Indies in the end! They were looking down and out at 114 for 7 but the lower order came to the party and took them home. This will be good for their confidence going forward and they have opened their account in the second cycle of the WTC. Earlier in the day, West Indies were 3 down for 16 runs.  Then it was a partnership between Roston Chase and Jermaine Blackwood that hold the game for the Windies. The former departed and the wickets started tumbling. Blackwood went on to score a half century but he too departed. Holder played a small cameo and went back. Joshua Da Silva and Kemar Roach stitched a partnership but Da Silva departed at the wrong time. It was then the Heroics of Roach that came into play. He was well supported by Warrican and Seales and they won.
AND BREATHE!!! Take a bow, Kemar Roach! He kept his nerves and did what no one believed. Credit to Jayden Seales also to hang in there with Roach. TEST MATCH AT ITS BEST.

He was unplayable and Pakistan would hope that he can continue that form. Mohammad Abbas was brilliant as well but could not find a wicket. Hasan Ali bowled a couple of wickets.
